04099nam a22008055i 9780823271276DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232712767 a10.1515/97808232712762doi  a(DE-B1597)555339  a(OCoLC)945121428  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB2430.F724 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a170.922231 aLynch, Richard A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFoucault's Critical Ethics /cRichard A. Lynch. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJust Ideas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Michel Foucault as Critical Theorist -- t1. Approaching Power from a New Theoretical Basis -- t2. Disciplinary Power: Testing the Hobbesian Hypothesis -- t3. Reframing the Theory: Biopower and Governmentality -- t4. Freedom's Critique: The Trajectories of a Foucauldian Ethics -- tConclusion. To Struggle with Hope -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe central thesis of Foucault's Critical Ethics is that Foucault's account of power does not foreclose the possibility of ethics; on the contrary, it provides a framework within which ethics becomes possible. Tracing the evolution of Foucault's analysis of power from his early articulations of disciplinary power to his theorizations of biopower and governmentality, Richard A. Lynch shows how Foucault's ethical project emerged through two interwoven trajectories: analysis of classical practices of the care of the self, and engaged practice in and reflection upon the limits of sexuality and the development of friendship in gay communities. These strands of experience and inquiry allowed Foucault to develop contrasting yet interwoven aspects of his ethics; they also underscored how ethical practice emerges within and from contexts of power relations. The gay community's response to AIDS and its parallels with the feminist ethics of care serve to illustrate the resources of a Foucauldian ethic-a fundamentally critical attitude, with substantive (but revisable) values and norms grounded in a practice of freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEthics. 0aPower (Philosophy) 0aPower (Philosophy). 4aBiopower. 4aCare. 4aDiscipline. 4aFoucault. 4aGovernmentality. 4acritique. 4aethics. 4afreedom. 4afriendship. 4apower. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327127640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823271276423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823271276.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK